'''EA Montreal''' is a Canadian [[video game developer|video game development studio]] owned and operated by [[Electronic Arts]]. The studio is based in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec|Québec]]. It was inaugurated by EA on March 17, 2004.<ref name="EAMontrealOpen">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/eas-montreal-studio-open-for-business-6091643|title=EA's Montreal Studio open for business|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|last=Navarro|first=Alex|date=2004-03-17|accessdate=2013-01-26}}</ref>

The studio was founded by Alain Tascan a former [[Ubisoft]] and [[BAM! Entertainment]] executive. It is one of a few examples where EA created a new studio instead of acquiring one. In 2006 with the acquisition of Jamdat, its Montreal offices were moved to the location of EA Montreal studio.

EA Montreal and EA Mobile Montreal are operated separately, however. In 2007, following the split of EA development studios into four labels, EA Montreal became part of EA Games Label ([[Frank Gibeau]], President). EA Montreal is responsible for two original franchises: ''[[Boogie (video game)|Boogie]]'' and ''[[Army of Two (series)|Army of Two]]'' as well as other titles where it collaborates with other EA studios.

The Visceral Montreal studio was closed in February 2013.<ref name="Gameinformer">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2013/02/21/report-army-of-two-developer-suffers-layoffs.aspx|title=Visceral Montreal Employee Confirms Entire Staff Let Go|last=Marchiafava|first=Jeff|publisher=[[Game Informer]]|date=2013-02-21|accessdate=2013-03-11}}</ref> In April 2012, EA announced layoffs in the Mobile division.<ref>{{cite web|last=Futter|first=Mike|title=[Updated] "Key Development Studio" EA Montreal&#39;s Mobile Division Hit With Layoffs - News - www.GameInformer.com|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2013/04/11/rumor-ea-montreal-mobile-division-hit-with-layoffs.aspx|work=Game Informer|publisher=GameStop Corporation|accessdate=15 September 2013}}</ref> A further layoff on the Mobile Division took place in February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/235973/Report_Layoffs_strike_EA_Montreal.php|title=Report: Layoffs strike EA Montreal|author=Alex Wawro |work=[[Gamasutra]]|date=2015-02-06|accessdate=2015-02-10}}</ref>

In July 2015, EA announced the creation of Motive Studios,<ref>http://www.ea.com/motivestudios/</ref> a new Montreal-based operation led by [[Jade Raymond]]. [[Motive Studios|Motive]] is co-located at EA Montreal with [[BioWare]], which has maintained a Montreal studio operation under the leadership of studio director Yanick Roy.

EA Montreal studio is located at 3 [[Place Ville-Marie]], downtown [[Montreal]].

[[File:Place Ville-Marie (toit au niveau de la rue) 2005-09-02.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The view of Place Ville-Marie 3 (on the right) - the location of EA Montreal]]

