This '''glossary of motion picture terms''' is a list of definitions of terms and concepts related to [[Film|motion pictures]], [[filmmaking]], [[cinematography]], and the [[film industry]] in general.

{{compact ToC|side=yes|center=yes|nobreak=yes|q=Q|u=U|y=Y|seealso=yes|refs=yes|num=yes|extlinks=yes}}

==0–9==

{{glossary}}
{{term|[[180-degree rule]]}}
{{defn|A basic guideline regarding the on-screen spatial relationship between a character and another character or object within a scene. By keeping the camera on one side of an imaginary axis between two characters, the first character is always {{gli|screen direction|frame right}} of the second character. Moving the camera over the axis is called ''jumping the line'' or ''crossing the line''; breaking the 180-degree rule by shooting on all sides is known as {{gli|shooting in the round}}.<ref>{{cite book |title=Film Directing Fundamentals |edition=2nd |last=Proferes |first=Nicholas T. |year=2005 |publisher=Focal Press |location=Amsterdam |isbn=978-0-240-80562-7 |page= |pages=5–7}}</ref>}}
{{term|[[30-degree rule]]}}
{{defn|A basic {{gli|editing|film editing}} guideline that states the camera should move at least 30 degrees relative to the subject between successive shots of the same subject. If the camera moves less than 30 degrees, the transition between shots may look like a {{gli|jump cut}}, which could jar the audience and take them out of the story by causing them to focus on the film technique rather than the narrative itself.<ref name="hollywoodlexicon">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodlexicon.com/thirtydegree.html|title=30 Degree Rule - Hollywood Lexicon|last=|first=|date=|website=www.hollywoodlexicon.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>}}
{{term|[[3D film]]}}
{{ghat|Also called a '''three-dimensional film''', '''three-dimensional stereoscopic film''', or '''S3D film'''.}}
{{defn|A type of {{gli|motion picture}} that utilizes special filming techniques to create the illusion of [[depth perception]], hence adding a [[third dimension]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118008671.html?categoryid=1009&cs=1 | work=Variety | title=Filmmakers like S3D's emotional wallop | first=508-831-6665David S. | last=Cohen | date=September 15, 2009}}</ref>}}
{{glossaryend}}

{{compact ToC|side=yes|center=yes|nobreak=yes|q=Q|u=U|y=Y|seealso=yes|refs=yes|num=yes|extlinks=yes}}

