{{term|[[below the line (film production)|below-the-line]]}}
{{defn|A term derived from the top sheet of a {{gli|film budgeting|film budget}} for {{gli|motion picture|motion pictures}}, [[television program]]s, {{gli|sponsored film|industrial films}}, {{gli|independent film|independent films}}, student films and {{gli|documentary film|documentaries}} as well as [[Advertisement film|commercials]]. The "line" in "below-the-line" refers to the separation of production costs between {{gli|screenwriter|script and story writers}}, {{gli|producer|producers}}, {{gli|director|directors}}, {{gli|actor|actors}} and {{gli|casting}} (collectively referred to as "{{gli|above-the-line}}") and the rest of the {{gli|film crew}} or [[production team]].<ref>{{cite web|title=What does "above/below the line" mean in a film budget?|url=https://www.quora.com/What-does-above-below-the-line-mean-in-a-film-budget|date= Feb 27, 2011|publisher=''[[Quora]]''|access-date=August 18, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=What does ‘below the line’ mean in movie production?|url=http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/what-does-below-line-mean-movie-production.htm|publisher=''[[How Stuff Works]]''|access-date=August 18, 2017 }}</ref>}}
