==C==

{{glossary}}
{{term|[[C-Clamp (stagecraft)|C-clamp]]}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[Callier effect]]}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[cameo appearance]]}}
{{defn|}}
{{term|[[cameo lighting]]}}
{{defn|A type of lighting whereby a {{gli|spotlight}} accentuates a single {{gli|character}} or other subject and sometimes a few props in a {{gli|scene}}, so that the focus of the scene is on the subject and not its surrounding environment. It is often used to create an "angelic" shot, such as one where a light used to represent God or heaven shines down onto the character. Cameo lighting derives its name from the art form in which a light relief figure is set against a darker background. It is often achieved by using {{gli|barn doors|barn-doored spotlights}}. A problem with cameo lighting is that it can lead to color distortion and noise in the darkest areas.<ref>Television Production Handbook, Zettl, pg. 173.</ref>
{{term|[[camera angle]]}}
{{defn|The specific location and position from which a {{gli|movie camera}} or {{gli|video camera}} is oriented to take a {{gli|shot}}. A single scene may be shot from several camera angles simultaneously.<ref name="Pincus">{{cite book|title=The Filmmaker's Handbook: A Comprehensive Guide for the Digital Age|last=Ascher|last2=Pincus|first2=Edward|publisher=Plume|year=1999|isbn=9781573221320|location=New York|page=214|first1=Steven}}<!--|accessdate=2015-12-10 --></ref>}}
