{{term|[[Dutch angle]]}}
{{ghat|Also called '''Dutch tilt''', '''canted angle''', or '''oblique angle'''.}}
{{defn|A type of camera shot where the camera is set at an angle on its roll axis so that the shot is composed with vertical lines at an angle to the side of the frame, or so that the horizon line of the shot is not parallel with the bottom of the camera frame. This produces a viewpoint akin to tilting one's head to the side.<ref name="auto">{{cite web|title=Dutch angle - Hollywood Lexicon|url=http://www.hollywoodlexicon.com/dutchangle.html|website=Hollywood Lexicon|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> In {{gli|cinematography}}, the Dutch angle is one of many [[cinematic techniques]] used to portray psychological uneasiness or tension in the subject being filmed.}}
