{{Infobox video game | collapsible = | state = | italic title = | title = Mountain | image = Mountain (video game) icon.png | alt = | developer = [[David OReilly (artist)|David OReilly]] | programmer = Damien Di Fede | publisher = [[Double Fine Productions]] | engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]] | platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], [[Linux]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]] | released = {{Video game release|WW|July 1, 2014}} | genre = [[Simulation game]] | modes = Single-player }}
'''''Mountain''''' is a [[simulation game|simulation video game]] developed by [[David OReilly (artist)|David OReilly]] and published by [[Double Fine Productions]]. It was released for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], [[Linux]], [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] in July 2014. The game is an [[idle game]] in which the only influence the player can have on the game is at the start of the game where the player is tasked to draw objects. The game is designed to be played in the background while the player uses other applications.
==Gameplay== ''Mountain'' is described by its creator [[David OReilly (artist)|David OReilly]] as a "Mountain Simulator, Relax em’ up, Art Horror etc." game, featuring little interactivity from the player.<ref name="atlantic">{{cite web | url = https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/07/you-are-mountain/374543/ | title = You Are Mountain | first = Ian | last = Bogost | date = July 17, 2014 | accessdate = April 3, 2017 | work = [[The Atlantic]]}}</ref> Upon starting the game, the player is asked to draw responses to a series of questions, described by OReilly as "more psychologically invasive than anything Facebook wants to know about you".<ref name="latimes reveal"/> The game uses that input to generate a model of a mountain, floating in space, surrounded by a small sphere of atmosphere. At this point, the game lacks significant interactivity; while the player can rotate the view around the mountain and zoom in and out, they cannot affect the mountain in any way. The game is set to be run in the background as the player does other activities on their computer.<ref name="atlantic"/>
Over the course of the game, the mountain slowly rotates as accelerated time progresses through day and night cycles and through seasonal changes: the player will see snow form and melt on the mountain, and plants trees grow and wither out. Randomly, the mountain may be hit by everyday objects which then become embedded in the mountain indefinitely. The mountain periodically offers its thoughts to the player as the game progresses.<ref name="atlantic"/> After around fifty hours while the game has been running, the mountain meets its fate when it crashes into a passing giant star, ending the game, at which point the player can start the game over with a new mountain.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://toucharcade.com/2014/07/09/spoiler-alert-i-just-beat-david-oreillys-mountain-and-got-it-on-video/ | title = Spoiler Alert: I Just Beat David O'Reilly's 'Mountain' and Got it On Video | first = Eli | last = Hodapp | date = July 9, 2014 | accessdate = April 3, 2017 | work = [[Touch Arcade]] }}</ref>
{{Multiple image | direction = horizontal | total_width = 600 | perrow = 2 | align = center | image1 = Mountain (video game) screenshot 1.jpg | image2 = Mountain (video game) screenshot 3.jpg | image3 = Mountain (video game) screenshot 9.jpg | image4 = Mountain Fast Photog.webm | footer = Screenshots and video of gameplay }}
==Development== David OReilly had developed a number of fictional video game sequences for the movie ''[[Her (film)|Her]]'' (2013). Following his involvement, OReilly had interest in creating a real video game, wanting "to explore in patterns and iterations of patterns".<ref name="latimes reveal">{{cite web | url = http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/miranda/la-et-cam-animator-from-her-makes-real-video-game-20140612-column.html| title = More invasive than Facebook: 'Mountain' from creator of games in 'Her' | first = Carolina | last = Miranda | date = June 12, 2014 | accessdate = April 3, 2017 | work = [[Los Angeles Times]] }}</ref> He considered the idea of simulating a mountain as "an iconic zen thing", and that the size of mountains dwarf that of the human experience;<ref name="latimes reveal"/> mountains further "defy objectification because they can't be owned or put in a museum".<ref name="gamasutra"/> OReilly described ''Mountain'' as "visual silence", and that it is "about letting go of control" while one watches the simulation.<ref name="gamasutra">{{cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/220443/There_is_nothing_to_do_in_OReillys_Mountain__and_thats_a_good_thing.php | title = There is nothing to 'do' in OReilly's Mountain - and that's a good thing | first = Leigh | last= Alexander | date = July 8, 2014 | accessdate = April 3, 2017 | work = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref>
To develop the game, OReilly started learning the [[Unity (game engine)|Unity engine]] himself. To complete ''Mountain'', gained assistance from Damien Di Fede who did most of the game's coding.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://motionographer.com/2014/07/15/david-oreilly-mountain/ | title = David O’Reilly: Mountain Q&A | first = Justin | last = Cone | date = July 14, 2014 | accessdate = April 3, 2017 | work = Motiongrapher }}</ref>
OReilly had revealed the game during the Horizon video game showcase held at the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles]] during the same week in June as the [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2014]].<ref name="latimes reveal"/> The game was published by [[Double Fine Productions]] under their "Double Fine Presents" label aimed for small [[independent video game|indie games]].<ref name="polygon release">{{cite web | url = http://www.polygon.com/2014/7/1/5861910/double-fine-publishes-her-game-creators-mountain-simulator-mountain | title = Double Fine publishes 'Her' game creator's mountain simulator, Mountain | first = Alexa Rae | last = Correira | date = July 1, 2014 | accessdate = April 3, 2017 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>
The title was initially released on July 1, 2014 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[OS X]], [[Linux]], and [[iOS]] platforms;<ref name="polygon release"/> the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] version was delayed until August 19, 2014 due to the cost of getting the Unity plugin for Android.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.androidpolice.com/2014/08/19/the-incredibly-bizarre-game-mountain-has-arrived-on-android/ | title = The Incredibly Bizarre Game MOUNTAIN Has Arrived On Android | first = Ryan | last = Whitwam | date = August 19, 2014 | accessdate = April 3, 2017 | work = [[Android Police]] }}</ref> OReilly had initially visioned the game to run as a background application for personal computers, and thus had not spent a great deal of time optimizing the [[iOS]] version through the [[Unity (game engine)|Unity engine]]. However, within a week of its release, ''Mountain'' was one of the top-selling titles on various [[app store]] charts, prompting OReilly to develop more optimization for the iOS and pending Android versions.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-07-07-barely-interactive-mountain-simulator-nearly-tops-the-ios-charts | title = Barely interactive "mountain simulator" nearly tops the iOS charts | first = Jeffrey | last = Matulef | date = July 7, 2014 | accessdate = April 3, 2017 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref>
==Reception== The game was generally praised by reviewers as a novel concept for a game,<ref name="atlantic"/><ref name="verge">{{cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2014/7/1/5857458/mountain-game | title= Playing a mountain simulator is surprisingly emotional | first = Andrew | last = Webster | date = July 1, 2014 | accessdate = April 3, 2017 | work =[[The Verge]]}}</ref><ref name="latimes">{{cite web | url = http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/miranda/la-et-cam-playing-her-animator-david-oreilly-mountain-video-game-20140705-column.html | title = Playing 'Her' animator David OReilly's hypnotic video game 'Mountain' | first = Carolina | last = Miranda | date = July 7, 2014 | accessdate = April 3, 2017 | work = [[Los Angeles Times]] }}</ref> though because of its limited interactivity, many players were discontent with the title, comparing it to a [[screensaver]] rather than a game.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pcgamer.com/why-the-media-loves-mountain-but-steam-users-are-calling-it-a-screensaver/ | title = Why critics love Mountain, but Steam users are calling it "worthless" | first = Tyler | last = Wilde | date = August 20, 2014 | accessdate = April 3, 2017 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref> Zack Kotzer of ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' compared the game to the [[Tamagotchi]] toys, though lacking the need to constantly attend to the toys' demands and instead letting the player decide when to see how the mountain is progressing.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/this-video-game-lets-you-own-your-own-tamagotchi-mountain | title = This Video Game Let's You Own Your Own Tamagotchi Mountain Pet | first= Zack | last = Kotzer | date = July 7, 2014 | accessdate = April 3, 2017 | work = [[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] }}</ref> Others described the title as a passive ''[[Katamari]]'' game, watching how the mountain accumulates stuff over the course of the game.<ref name="verge"/><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.usgamer.net/articles/before-everything-there-was-just-a-mountain- | title = Before Everything, There Was Just A Mountain | first = Caty | last = McCarthy | date = March 28, 2017 | accessdate = April 3, 2017 | work = [[US Gamer]] }}</ref> Some reviewers found the title pretentious; Ben Kuchera of ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' felt the game may have been a joke by OReilly, and expressed he lacked the same type of wonder that other journalist had found for the game.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.polygon.com/2014/7/3/5868087/mountain-indie-game-joke-satire-self-loathing | title = Mountain could be a $1 joke, and I think I'm the butt | first= Ben | last = Kuchera | date = July 3, 2014 | accessdate = April 3, 2017 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>
